    "Command Actor": {
      "value": "State/coalition",
      "memo": "The UK training constraint reflects state-level policy choices about copyright and data governance, not enterprise decisions.",
      "detail": "The training limitation is created by UK government copyright and regulatory policy. Individual enterprises cannot override the jurisdictional data-availability constraint. State-level command over training conditions differentiates from enterprise-level deployment decisions. The constraint is a sovereign policy choice with industrial consequences."
    },
    "Decision Tempo": {
      "value": "Product cycle",
      "memo": "UK AI regulatory decisions follow policy and legislative timelines rather than crisis or product-release cadence.",
      "detail": "Copyright reform and AI governance policy development follow parliamentary and administrative timelines. These policy processes operate more slowly than the AI industry's development pace. Product-cycle tempo at the deployment layer is faster than the policy tempo setting training conditions. The mismatch between policy tempo and technology tempo compounds the constraint."
    },
    "Tradeoff Authority": {
      "value": "Safety body",
      "memo": "UK AI safety institutions like AISI advise on training tradeoffs, but copyright policy is set by IP legislation rather than safety review.",
      "detail": "AISI evaluates frontier model safety but does not determine data-access rules. Copyright policy is set through IP legislation and court decisions. The training constraint emerges from IP law rather than AI safety considerations. Safety-body tradeoff authority applies to deployment risks, not data-access permissions."
    },
    "Permission": {
      "value": "Conditional",
      "memo": "UK training permission is conditional on copyright consent: no broad fair-use defense exists for commercial AI training.",
      "detail": "UK copyright does not provide a fair-use equivalent for commercial AI training. The text-and-data-mining exception is limited to non-commercial research. Commercial training requires explicit rights-holder consent for each copyrighted work. This conditional permission is the core constraint that makes UK training unattractive."
    },
    "Regulatory Posture": {
      "value": "Prohibitive",
      "memo": "The UK regulatory posture is effectively prohibitive for broad LLM training: copyright obligations make internet-scale training legally hazardous.",
      "detail": "While not explicitly banned, broad LLM training using UK-sourced data faces prohibitive legal risk. Rights-holder organizations actively monitor and enforce copyright against AI training. The cumulative effect of copyright obligations makes the posture functionally prohibitive. Prohibitive is the practical classification even though the legal framework is technically conditional."
    },
    "Data Availability": {
      "value": "Blocked",
      "memo": "UK-sourced training data is effectively blocked for large-scale commercial training: copyright requirements make broad data access unviable.",
      "detail": "No legal mechanism provides bulk access to UK copyrighted content for commercial AI training. Individual licensing negotiations with thousands of rights holders are impractical at training scale. The blocked status is the practical consequence of conditional permission without a bulk-access mechanism. Data availability is the binding constraint, not compute access."
    },
    "Provenance": {
      "value": "Mixed/declared",
      "memo": "Any UK-based training effort would require mixed-provenance data with some licensed, some public-domain, creating declaration obligations.",
      "detail": "A compliant UK training corpus would need documented provenance for every content source. Some data would be licensed, some public-domain, some openly licensed. The mixed-provenance requirement adds administrative cost to the legal-risk burden. Declaration obligations compound the practical difficulty of UK-based training."
    },
    "Model-Weight Rights": {
      "value": "Hosted only",
      "memo": "UK enterprises access AI through hosted API models, avoiding the training-layer constraints by consuming externally trained capability.",
      "detail": "Hosted-only access through APIs from US-based providers is the practical workaround for the training constraint. UK enterprises consume AI capability without needing to navigate UK training-data requirements. The hosted-only model shifts the training-rights burden to the model provider's home jurisdiction. Weight access terms are set by the provider rather than UK-specific requirements."
    },
    "Territory": {
      "value": "Domestic",
      "memo": "The training constraint is territorial: UK copyright applies to data sourced from UK-jurisdiction content and rights holders.",
      "detail": "UK copyright obligations apply to content created or published under UK law. The domestic territorial scope means the constraint applies specifically to UK-sourced training data. Training on non-UK data could avoid some UK copyright constraints. The territorial nature of the constraint suggests that training is better done in more permissive jurisdictions."
    },
    "Data Subject Exposure": {
      "value": "Ordinary personal data",
      "memo": "UK training data contains ordinary personal data triggering UK GDPR obligations alongside copyright constraints.",
      "detail": "Web content from UK sources frequently contains personal information. UK GDPR obligations layer on top of copyright requirements for training data. Personal-data exposure adds a second regulatory constraint beyond copyright. The combination of copyright and privacy obligations compounds the training difficulty."
    },
    "Data Sensitivity": {
      "value": "Sensitive/regulated",
      "memo": "UK regulatory sensitivity classifications for training data include both copyright-protected creative works and regulated personal information.",
      "detail": "Creative works under UK copyright are commercially sensitive assets for rights holders. Personal data within training corpora triggers regulated-data classification under UK GDPR. The combination creates a heightened sensitivity profile for any UK-sourced training corpus. Sensitive-regulated classification reflects the layered regulatory burden."
    },
    "Control Exposure": {
      "value": "No control issue",
      "memo": "UK LLM training does not trigger export-control concerns; the constraint is copyright and data protection, not dual-use classification.",
      "detail": "The training constraint comes from IP and privacy law, not from export-control or dual-use classification. No export-control issue prevents UK-based training from a technology-restriction perspective. The constraint is entirely about data access, not technology control. Control exposure is a separate concern from the data-availability problem."
    },
    "Processing Mode": {
      "value": "Training",
      "memo": "The constraint specifically targets training as the processing mode: it is the act of training on UK-copyrighted data that creates legal risk.",
      "detail": "Training is the processing mode that triggers copyright consent requirements. Inference on an externally trained model does not face the same UK copyright constraints. The distinction between training and inference is the hinge of the UK constraint. This is why the stance describes a training constraint, not a deployment constraint."
    },
    "Derivation": {
      "value": "Recursive derivation",
      "memo": "LLM training creates recursive derivation from copyrighted input, which is precisely what UK copyright law makes problematic.",
      "detail": "Training transforms copyrighted works into model weights that generate derivative outputs. These outputs can recursively generate further training data and model improvements. The recursive derivation chain from copyrighted input is what triggers rights-holder concerns. UK law provides no safe harbor for this recursive transformation of protected works."
    },
    "Retention / Persistence": {
      "value": "Weight-entangled",
      "memo": "Training creates weight-entangled persistence: copyrighted data becomes inseparable from model capability, which is the termination trap.",
      "detail": "Once copyrighted data is trained into weights, the capability persists regardless of license status. No reliable method extracts specific copyrighted contributions from trained weights. This weight entanglement is why UK rights holders view training as a permanent appropriation. The persistence problem makes training-rights disputes practically irresolvable."
    },
