    "Switching Cost": {
      "value": "Low",
      "memo": "UK enterprises face low switching costs between external model providers since they do not depend on domestically trained models.",
      "detail": "Consumer-style API access means UK enterprises can switch between model providers easily. No domestic training investment creates switching-cost lock-in. Low switching costs are a side effect of the application-only positioning. The switching-cost profile reflects import dependence rather than strategic choice."
    },
    "Exit": {
      "value": "Capability entangled",
      "memo": "The training constraint exists precisely because exit from training is capability-entangled: trained capability persists after data-rights termination.",
      "detail": "The persistence of trained capability after license termination is what makes rights holders demand consent before training. Weight entanglement means that training creates permanent capability appropriation. This is the fundamental tension: training is a one-way transformation of copyrighted content. The capability-entangled exit is both the problem definition and the reason the constraint exists."
    },
    "Acceptance Basis": {
      "value": "Process-required",
      "memo": "The UK training constraint is itself a process-legitimacy demand: rights-holder and regulatory process blocks regardless of outcomes.",
      "detail": "Copyright holders and the ICO require documented permission and lawful basis before training on UK-sourced data. The constraint operates as a gate: no amount of beneficial output legitimises unauthorised training. Process compliance is the precondition, not a supplement to outcome quality. This makes the UK training environment structurally process-required regardless of political rhetoric about innovation."
    }
  }
}
